To add a coverage badge to your README, you’ll connect your GitHub workflow’s coverage reports with a badge provider like Codecov or Coveralls. Since we already set up coverage reporting in your workflow, here’s how to integrate the badge:

---

🔧 Step 1: Upload Coverage to Codecov
In your workflow, after running tests, add:

`yaml
      - name: Upload coverage to Codecov
        uses: codecov/codecov-action@v4
        with:
          token: ${{ secrets.CODECOV_TOKEN }}
          files: ./coverage.xml
          failciif_error: true
`

- Create a secret CODECOV_TOKEN in your GitHub repo.  
- This sends coverage results to Codecov’s dashboard.

---

📌 Step 2: Add Badge to README.md
Once Codecov is connected, it provides a badge URL. Add this Markdown snippet at the top of your README:

`markdown
![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/USERNAME/REPO)
`

Replace:
- USERNAME → your GitHub username/org  
- REPO → your repository name  
- YOURTOKEN → the token provided by Codecov  

---

📂 Example README with Badges
`markdown

CrystalCastle

![Build Status](https://github.com/USERNAME/REPO/actions)
![Coverage Status](https://codecov.io/gh/USERNAME/REPO)
![PyPI version](https://pypi.org/project/crystalcastle/)
![License: MIT](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)
`

---

🚀 Result
- Badge updates automatically after each workflow run.  
- Clicking the badge opens the Codecov dashboard with detailed coverage reports.  
- Your README now shows real-time test coverage alongside build and version info.  

